-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt; list-style-type: decimal;\"><strong style=\"background-image: initial; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt;\">Lift your hips</strong><span style=\"background-image: initial; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt;\" data-preserver-spaces=\"true\">: Engage your core and lift your hips off the floor, creating a straight line from your head to your heels. Avoid letting your hips sag or rotate.</span></li>\r\n<li style=\"background-image: initial; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt; list-style-type: decimal;\"><strong style=\"background-image: initial; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt;\">Hold the position</strong><span style=\"background-image: initial; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt;\" data-preserver-spaces=\"true\">: Maintain the side plank with your feet on the bench, keeping your body aligned and stable. Focus on keeping your core tight and your body in a straight line.</span></li>\r\n</ol>', '', 'Bodyweight, Bodyweight', 1, 4, NULL, 'uploads/image/1730666395Screenshot_70.png', 'URL', 'server', 'https://youtu.be/oN1MeZFLtGE', 'Y', '2024-11-03 20:39:56', 'uploads/thumb/17306663951730666395screenshot_70.png', 3, 'Hip Adductors', NULL, NULL, 1, 1),
(75, 7, 'Closed/open grip front rack split squat', 'A closed grip can be a useful alternative if the front rack position is uncomfortable or difficult to maintain.', '<ol style=\"color: #0e101a; background-image: initial; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt;\">\r\n<li style=\"background-image: initial; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt; list-style-type: decimal;\"><strong style=\"background-image: initial; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt;\">Set up the bar</strong><span style=\"background-image: initial; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt;\" data-preserver-spaces=\"true\">: Position the bar across your clavicles in a closed or open front rack position, with your elbows high (closed grip) or slightly lower (open grip).</span></li>\r\n<li style=\"background-image: initial; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt; list-style-type: decimal;\"><strong style=\"background-image: initial; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt;\">Step into position</strong><span style=\"background-image: initial; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt;\" data-preserver-spaces=\"true\">: Take a controlled step forward or backwards, ensuring a stable base.</span></li>\r\n<li style=\"background-image: initial; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt; list-style-type: decimal;\"><strong style=\"background-image: initial; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt;\">Lower into a squat</strong><span style=\"background-image: initial; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt;\" data-preserver-spaces=\"true\">: Drop your hips, bringing the back knee toward the floor while keeping the front shin vertical and torso upright, maintaining the front rack position.</span></li>\r\n<li style=\"background-image: initial; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt; list-style-type: decimal;\"><strong style=\"background-image: initial; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt;\">Stand back up</strong><span style=\"background-image: initial; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt;\" data-preserver-spaces=\"true\">: Push through the front foot to return to the starting position, keeping the bar stable and your posture intact.</span></li>\r\n<li style=\"background-image: initial; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt; list-style-type: decimal;\"><strong style=\"background-image: initial; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt;\">Repeat</strong><span style=\"background-image: initial; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt;\" data-preserver-spaces=\"true\">: Continue on one side or alternate legs, maintaining control throughout.</span></li>\r\n</ol>', '', 'Barbell', 5, 4, NULL, 'uploads/image/1730666787Screenshot_71.png', 'URL', 'server', 'https://youtu.be/hv5EPiw8JX8', 'Y', '2024-11-03 20:46:27', 'uploads/thumb/17306667871730666787screenshot_71.png', 3, 'All Muscles Used', NULL, NULL, 1, 1),
(76, 7, 'Chin up', 'Chin-ups are often mistaken for pull-ups, but the key difference lies in the grip variation. Resistance bands can be used to regress the movement and assist with the pull.', '<ol style=\"color: #0e101a; background-image: initial; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt;\">\r\n<li style=\"background-image: initial; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt; list-style-type: decimal;\"><strong style=\"background-image: initial; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt;\">Set your grip</strong><span style=\"background-image: initial; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt;\" data-preserver-spaces=\"true\">: Grab the pull-up bar with your hands shoulder-width apart, palms facing you (supine grip). Your thumbs should wrap around the bar for a secure hold.</span></li>\r\n<li style=\"background-image: initial; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt; list-style-type: decimal;\"><strong style=\"background-image: initial; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt;\">Engage your shoulders</strong><span style=\"background-image: initial; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt;\" data-preserver-spaces=\"true\">: Pull your shoulder blades down and back before starting the movement, keeping your shoulders engaged. </span><span style=\"background-image: initial; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt;\" data-preserver-spaces=\"true\">This</span><span style=\"background-image: initial; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt;\" data-preserver-spaces=\"true\"> helps prevent unnecessary strain on your shoulders and activates the back muscles.</span></li>\r\n<li style=\"background-image: initial; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt; list-style-type: decimal;\"><strong style=\"background-image: initial; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt;\">Hang with arms extended</strong><span style=\"background-image: initial; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt;\" data-preserver-spaces=\"true\">: Start from a dead hang with your arms fully extended, body in a straight line, and legs hanging or slightly bent to prevent swinging.</span></li>\r\n<li style=\"background-image: initial; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt; list-style-type: decimal;\"><strong style=\"background-image: initial; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt;\">Pull your chin to the bar</strong><span style=\"background-image: initial; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt;\" data-preserver-spaces=\"true\">: Initiate the pull by driving your elbows down and back, bringing your chin as close to the bar as possible. Focus on using your back muscles rather than just your arms to perform the movement.</span></li>\r\n<li style=\"background-image: initial; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt; list-style-type: decimal;\"><strong style=\"background-image: initial; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt;\">Reach the top position</strong><span style=\"background-image: initial; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt;\" data-preserver-spaces=\"true\">: Continue pulling until your chin is above